=========================================================
CONSTRUCTOR CALL ORDER
=========================================================

class Base
{
public:
    Base()
    {
        cout << "Base\n";
    }
};

class Derived : public Base
{
public:
    Derived()
    {
        cout << "Derived\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Derived d;
}

Output:

Base
Derived

Rule:
Base constructor executes first.

Why is the base constructor called before the derived constructor?

Because a Derived object contains a Base subobject. The Base part must be fully constructed 
and initialized before the Derived part can use it. Therefore, C++ always constructs 
objects from Base to Derived and destroys them in reverse order (Derived to Base).

=========================================================
DESTRUCTOR CALL ORDER
=========================================================

class Base
{
public:
    ~Base()
    {
        cout << "Base\n";
    }
};

class Derived : public Base
{
public:
    ~Derived()
    {
        cout << "Derived\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Derived d;
}

Output:

Derived
Base

Rule:
Destructor order is reverse.

